{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487157"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:59:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:59:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"266"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/266"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.09,0.12,0.11,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"266"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97369"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/266"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"266"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79984"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2375"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"6625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9597"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32563"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44252"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97369"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with increasing fatigue and pallor over the past three months. He has also noted mild abdominal pain and constipation against a family history of bowel cancer. He has a medical history of mechanical mitral valve replacement three months ago for severe mitral regurgitation, hypertension, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. His medications include warfarin and perindopril. On examination, he appears pale but not distressed. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 120/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. There is conjunctival pallor. Heart sounds are dual with a mechanical click and systolic murmur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehaemoglobin 90 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Emean corpuscular volume 98 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eplatelet count: 180 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (140-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ereticulocyte percentage: 4.5% (0.2-2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ereticulocyte count: 180 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (10-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Elactate dehydrogenase: 401 units/L (120-250)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehaptoglobin: 0.1 g/L (0.3-2.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Edirect antiglobulin test (DAT): negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ecoagulation profile and fibrinogen within normal limits\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe blood smear is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of the anaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mechanical haemolysis","Chronic blood loss","Hereditary spherocytosis","Warm autoimmune haemolytic anaemia","Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with signs and symptoms of anaemia, with laboratory features of non-immune haemolysis. Haemolytic anaemia occurs due to premature destruction of red blood cells (RBC). This causes raised unconjugated bilirubin, LDH, and reduced haptoglobin due to the binding of free haemoglobin. Anaemia in this setting is commonly normocytic. However, macrocytosis can be seen due to reticulocytosis (bigger than mature RBC) or concomitant B12/folate deficiency. The blood smear shows schistocytes. DAT is helpful in distinguishing immune versus non-immune haemolysis, as shown in \u003Cem\u003ETable 1\u003C/em\u003E adapted from Palmer et al. (1).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMechanical haemolysis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause given the recent mechanical mitral valve replacement (six months ago), non-immune haemolysis (negative DAT), and schistocytes on blood film. Mechanical heart valves can cause shear stress on red blood cells as they pass through the valve, leading to fragmentation (schistocytes) and intravascular haemolysis. This typically occurs within the first few months after valve replacement, which aligns with this patient\u0027s timeline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic blood loss\u003C/strong\u003E is a major cause of iron deficiency anaemia in the elderly population. This needs to be considered, given his abdominal symptoms. However, microcytic anaemia would be expected without features of haemolysis: raised LDH, unconjugated bilirubin, and reduced haptoglobin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Ehereditary spherocytosis\u003C/strong\u003E, RBC membrane proteins are defective (e.g., ankyrin, spectrin), resulting in extravascular damage. Hence, spherocytes are seen rather than schistocytes. It is most commonly inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern. The DAT would be negative in this case due to non-immune mediated haemolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarm autoimmune haemolytic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E would show a positive DAT specific for immunoglobulin G. Peripheral blood smear shows spherocytes rather than schistocytes reflecting extravascular destruction of RBC predominantly in the spleen. In the elderly, lymphoproliferative disorders, especially chronic lymphocytic leukaemia, is a common cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by MAHA, thrombocytopenia, neurological changes (e.g., confusion), and gastrointestinal symptoms (e.g., diarrhoea). In contrast to atypical haemolytic uremic syndrome, acute kidney injury is rare. In this case, the normal platelet count and absence of neurological changes make TTP unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Haemolytic anaemia is suggested by normocytic/macrocytic anaemia, raised unconjugated bilirubin, LDH, and reduced haptoglobin.","Direct antiglobulin test (DAT) helps distinguish between immune and non-immune mediated haemolysis. In non-immune haemolysis, DAT is negative.","Mechanical stress from mechanical heart valves, severe aortic stenosis, or prolonged marching can cause non-immune, extracorpuscular haemolytic anaemia."],"references":["Palmer D, Seviar D. How to approach haemolysis: Haemolytic anaemia for the general physician. Clinical Medicine. 2022;22(3):210-3.","Phillips J, Henderson AC. Hemolytic Anemia: Evaluation and Differential Diagnosis. Am Fam Physician. 2018 Sep 15;98(6):354\u201361.","Doust J. Diagnostic and management strategies for anaemia in adults. Aust Fam Physician. 2003 Nov;32(11):889\u201394.","Beris P, Picard V. Non-immune Hemolysis: Diagnostic Considerations. Semin Hematol. 2015 Oct;52(4):287\u2013303."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79984"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"266"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20354"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20369"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20354"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cvIYwXy9d6DyY9WdwEnXWHixQG70Hn.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cvIYwXy9d6DyY9WdwEnXWHixQG70Hn.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1066}},{"type":"media","id":"20369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20369"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/mOfBuQp4hskHjN46UDHFOaja90ambT.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/mOfBuQp4hskHjN46UDHFOaja90ambT.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":650}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79984"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T13:06:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T13:08:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"266"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97369"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type